AR14 - Fondazione Berio

The Fondazione Berio is a theoretical project for a public building designed to archive sound documents for RAI (Radiotelevisione Italiana). It appears as a large treasure chest, a blind box where functional archive spaces, sound production and restoration areas, and listening and consultation spaces coexist.The building follows a clear spatial organisation. The ground floor, framed by eight imposing concrete shafts, houses an open, multi-purpose space including a café, a terrace, a reception area and a cloakroom. On the first floor, the main space, a large atrium, is surrounded by a ring of individual listening spaces on which rest seven floors of archives and a level dedicated to the production and restoration of sound documents.The emblematic feature of the building is a modular acoustic ceiling that hangs over the atrium. Able to be adjusted in height, it transforms the atrium into an auditorium, allowing sound content to be broadcast under controlled and varied acoustic conditions. The project pays particular attention to detail, with the edges of the archive compactors designed as acoustic panels, and the handrails in the archive spaces also serving as technical trellises for the sound and lighting equipment. Choices that reflect a desire for balance and dialogue between the different functions of the building, where each programme enriches the other. The Fondazione Berio thus stands for a harmonious cohabitation between storage and listening, designed to enhance the experience of sound archives within a coherent whole.